{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a98a978b-8ea6-440f-8170-cc516eb6b40a","content":"Here's what needs to change:\n\n**`.csproj`** — Replace the old assembly reference and separate `Test.Sdk` package with the single MSTest v3 metapackage:\n\n1. **Remove** the assembly reference to `Microsoft.VisualStudio.QualityTools.UnitTestFramework`\n2. **Remove** `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` (bundled in MSTest v3)\n3. **Add** `<PackageReference Include=\"MSTest\" Version=\"3.8.2\" />`\n\n**`.cs` files** — No changes needed. MSTest v3 keeps the same `Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting` namespace, so your `[TestClass]`, `[TestMethod]`, `Assert.*` calls all work as-is.\n\nWant me to apply these changes and verify the project builds/tests pass?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"568945f6-98af-4df3-b34a-4a00eabb3f56","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has:\n1. A `.csproj` targeting `net462` with an assembly reference to `Microsoft.VisualStudio.QualityTools.UnitTestFramework`\n2. A `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` package reference at version 17.5.0\n3. Test code using `Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting` namespace\n\nTo upgrade to MSTest v3, they need to:\n\n1. **Remove** the old assembly reference to `Microsoft.VisualStudio.QualityTools.UnitTestFramework`\n2. **Add** the `MSTest` NuGet package (v3.x) — MSTest v3 ships as a single `MSTest` metapackage that includes the test framework, adapter, and test SDK\n\n\n3. **Keep the target framework** — MSTest v3 supports `net462` and above, so their current setup is compatible.\n4. **Simplify the test SDK reference** — Since the `MSTest` v3 package bundles everything together, they can remove or consolidate the separate `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` reference.\n\nThe key insight is that MSTest v3 consolidated all three packages (`MSTest.TestFramework`, `MSTest.TestAdapter`, and `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk`) into a single `MSTest` NuGet package, and the namespace remains unchanged. So the migration path is straightfo